00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:09.870
Remember, at each event node we wanna
find the outcome with the minimum value.

223
00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:12.130
We wanna see how bad things can get.

224
00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:15.940
If we look down at the bottom,
we can see when the market is weak or

225
00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:18.630
strong for supplier P.

226
00:15:18.630 --> 00:15:24.390
The worst outcome is when the market is
weak and the idea loses 300,000 euros.

227
00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:28.310
So we'll replace that event
node with the 300,000.

228
00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:32.400
Moving up now to supplier S,
if the market is weak or

229
00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:36.870
the market is strong,
IDEA always earns 150,000 euros.

230
00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:42.020
So, in this case, the minimum and
the maximum value are both 150,000.

231
00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:45.470
Finally, there's nothing to do
if IDEA contracts with no one.

232
00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:48.000
Because we already know
that IDEA makes no money.

233
00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:54.427
The last step of determining the maxi-min
set of decisions is to go and

234
00:15:54.427 --> 00:15:56.584
look at the decision nodes.

235
00:15:56.584 --> 00:15:58.899
Here there's one last decision node, and

236
00:15:58.899 --> 00:16:02.319
we wanna find the action that
maximizes the associated value.

237
00:16:02.319 --> 00:16:04.548
That decision's who to contract with.

238
00:16:04.548 --> 00:16:10.470
And we can see the value maximizing
decision is to contract with supplier s.

239
00:16:10.470 --> 00:16:13.370
So what we'll do is
we'll cut away those two

240
00:16:13.370 --> 00:16:18.050
little red lines that are supposed
to be cuts on branches of the tree,

241
00:16:18.050 --> 00:16:23.900
to indicate that we've chosen contracting
with supplier s as the maxi min strategy.

242
00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:29.900
The next strategy that we'll demonstrate
is the maxi-max set of decisions.

243
00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:35.850
Remember, maxi-max set of decisions
maximize the value of the maximum outcome.

244
00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:39.820
So we want to see how good we can
make the best possible outcome.

245
00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:43.200
To roll back a maxi-max decision tree,

246
00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:47.970
we again start with the tree's outcomes
and work backwards towards its root.

247
00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:52.290
At each event node, we now find
the outcome with the maximum value and

248
00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:55.170
we replace the event node
with that maximum value.

249
00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:57.500
Then at each decision node as before,

250
00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:00.770
we choose the action that
maximizes the associated value.

251
00:17:02.190 --> 00:17:05.810
So let's take a look and
see what happens with IDEAS decision tree.

252
00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:10.980
Again, we start at the tree's outcomes and
we work backwards towards its root.

253
00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:13.400
Starting at the outcomes and
moving to the left,

254
00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:16.390
we see that the first set
of nodes are event nodes.

255
00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:17.710
We'll start at the bottom.

256
00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:22.280
We'll evaluate the decision
to contract with supplier P.

257
00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.130
Remember, at this event node,
we going to look for

258
00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:27.190
the outcome with the maximum value.

259
00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:34.600
And for IDEA, that maximum value is
450,000 euros when the market is strong.

260
00:17:34.600 --> 00:17:36.480
So we'll replace that event node.

261
00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:38.440
And now we'll move to supplier S.

262
00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:43.220
Again, in either case,
the outcome is 150,000 euros.

263
00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:50.510
So, by contracting with supplier S,
the maximum value is 150,000 euros.

264
00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:55.870
And finally, we'll move to the decision
node, which is whom to contract with,

265
00:17:55.870 --> 00:17:59.740
and we'll choose the action that
maximizes the associated value.

266
00:17:59.740 --> 00:18:04.920
In this case, you can see
the maximum value is 450,000 euros,

267
00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:07.080
for contracting with supplier P.

268
00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:11.260
And so, we'll eliminate the other two
choices contracting with no one or

269
00:18:11.260 --> 00:18:13.160
contracting with supplier S.

270
00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:17.500
That is, the maxi-max strategy
is to contract the supplier P.

271
00:18:18.830 --> 00:18:24.240
Finally, we're going to determine what
the expected value maximizing strategy is.

272
00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:27.900
We'll start at the tree's outcomes and
work backwards towards its root.

273
00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:32.080
At each event node, we'll now calculate
the expected value of the outcomes, and

274
00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:35.090
we'll replace the event node
with that expected value.

275
00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:37.190
How do we calculate the expected value?

276
00:18:37.190 --> 00:18:39.110
We take each of the outcomes and

277
00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:43.080
we weight it by the estimate of
the probability that it will occur.

278
00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:46.750
At each decision node we'll then
choose the action that maximizes

279
00:18:46.750 --> 00:18:48.280
the associated value.

280
00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:50.880
So let's take a look at how it works for
idea.

281
00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:54.600
Again we'll start at the tree outcomes and
work backwards towards it's root.

282
00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:58.410
The first set of nodes we
see are event nodes, and

283
00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:02.670
first we'll evaluate the event
node associated with supplier P.

284
00:19:02.670 --> 00:19:05.040
And we'll calculate the expected value.

285
00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:07.980
The outcomes are four
hundred fifty thousand, and

286
00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:09.620
negative three hundred thousand.

287
00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:12.670
And we need to weight them by
the probabilities that they occur.

288
00:19:12.670 --> 00:19:13.890
Point five each.

289
00:19:13.890 --> 00:19:21.700
The calculation is that we take
.05*(450,000)+ .05*(-300,000) to

290
00:19:21.700 --> 00:19:27.540
get an expected value of 75,000 for
contracting with supplier p.

291
00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:30.560
Well take that expected value and
substitute it for

292
00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:33.830
the event node and move up to supplier s.

293
00:19:33.830 --> 00:19:38.870
The same calculation for
supplier s has 150,000 for both outcomes.

294
00:19:38.870 --> 00:19:41.440
And it's not hard to see
that when we weight both

295
00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:45.670
outcomes by 0.5 the expected
value is also 150,000.

296
00:19:45.670 --> 00:19:50.970
We'll take that expected value and
replace the event node by it.

297
00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:57.480
And finally we can decide who Idea should
contract with to maximize expected value.

298
00:19:57.480 --> 00:20:01.620
Here you can see the expected
value that highest is 150,000.

299
00:20:01.620 --> 00:20:03.880
That's contracting with supplier S.

300
00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:06.580
And so
we'll eliminate the two other options.

301
00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:12.270
The expected value maximizing strategy for
idea is to contract with supplier S.

302
00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:15.460
So those are the three strategies.

303
00:20:15.460 --> 00:20:21.000
Maximin, maximax, and
expected value maximizing strategies.

304
00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.200
The maxi-min strategy was
to chose supplier S, and

305
00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:26.950
it had a maxi-min value of 150,000 Euros.

306
00:20:26.950 --> 00:20:32.010
That is, that was the strategy that would
ensure that the worst that could happen

307
00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:35.140
would be IDEA would earn 150,000 Euros.

308
00:20:35.140 --> 00:20:38.240
The maxi-max strategy
was to chose supplier P,

309
00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:42.846
and it had a maxi-max
value of 450,000 Euros.

310
00:20:42.846 --> 00:20:46.630
The maxi-max strategy ensures

311
00:20:46.630 --> 00:20:51.076
that idea has the chance of
earning up to 450,000 euros.

312
00:20:51.076 --> 00:20:55.300
Finally the risk-neutral strategy
was to choose supplier S.

313
00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:59.068
And again,
it had an expected value of 150,000 euros.

314
00:20:59.068 --> 00:21:02.600
So you can see the maxi-min strategy and

315
00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:06.120
the risk-neutral strategy
have the same value.

316
00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:10.850
That is the expected value
maximizing strategy is also

317
00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:15.520
a very safe strategy because it's
also maximizing the minimum payout.

318
00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:19.640
We've completed the building and
the analysis of the decision tree, and

319
00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:24.530
it's a good point to review the mechanics
of what we do to analyse decision trees.

320
00:21:24.530 --> 00:21:27.300
First we construct a decision tree.

321
00:21:27.300 --> 00:21:29.160
A decision tree has three parts.

322
00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:33.850
It has decision nodes, those are points
at which you make choices among options.

323
00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:38.540
It has event nodes, those are moments in
time when there's a random occurrence.

324
00:21:38.540 --> 00:21:40.070
And finally, there are outcomes.

325
00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:44.290
They capture all the costs and rewards
leading up to each leaf of the tree.

326
00:21:44.290 --> 00:21:47.520
Having built the decision tree,
we just take a look at it.

327
00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:50.480
And looking at the range of outcomes and
the probabilities,

328
00:21:50.480 --> 00:21:52.260
itself can be instructive.

329
00:21:52.260 --> 00:21:55.130
But for a very big tree,
it's useful to have

330
00:21:55.130 --> 00:22:01.080
a more systematic way of taking
a look at the range of possibilities.

331
00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:05.330
And to do that we use three classic
decision making strategies,

332
00:22:05.330 --> 00:22:10.870
to look at risk seeking, risk avoiding and
risk neutral strategies.

333
00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:14.050
For all three of them, we started
at the end with the outcomes, and

334
00:22:14.050 --> 00:22:15.970
worked backwards to the root.

335
00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:19.990
At event notes,
we then calculated either the minimum,

336
00:22:19.990 --> 00:22:24.911
the maximum value or the expected value,
and that differed with the max/min,

337
00:22:24.911 --> 00:22:28.680
max/max, or
expected value maximizing strategy.

338
00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:29.210
And finally,

339
00:22:29.210 --> 00:22:33.140
at decision nodes, we cut away the
decision that did not maximize the value.

340
00:22:34.250 --> 00:22:39.320
This procedure identifies a range of
risk-sensitive strategies from highly risk

341
00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:45.380
avoiding max/min strategies,
to risk-seeking maxi max strategies,

342
00:22:45.380 --> 00:22:50.360
to expected value maximizing strategies
that are somewhere in between.

343
00:22:50.360 --> 00:22:54.430
When using decision trees, it's also
worth keeping the following in mind.

344
00:22:54.430 --> 00:22:58.210
The tree that we constructed in
this session was quite small.

345
00:22:58.210 --> 00:23:01.060
Specifically so
that it all could fit on one screen.

346
00:23:01.060 --> 00:23:04.050
But in real life decision trees
can be very, very large and

347
00:23:04.050 --> 00:23:07.810
have many branches and
layers of decisions and events.

348
00:23:07.810 --> 00:23:12.460
Cash flows in decision trees sometimes
stream in over long periods of time.

349
00:23:12.460 --> 00:23:17.690
Like years, In that case you need to worry
about the discounting of the cash flows.

350
00:23:17.690 --> 00:23:20.890
Where do the cash flows and probabilities
come from in the first place?

351
00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:22.610
Sometimes it comes from past data.

352
00:23:22.610 --> 00:23:27.790
For example, maybe IDEA had sold tents
similar to the Krusbar in previous years.

353
00:23:27.790 --> 00:23:29.970
Sometimes it comes from "expert judgment".

354
00:23:29.970 --> 00:23:35.070
But in either case, these are predictions
about cash flows and probabilities, and

355
00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:38.540
that's a form of "predictive" analytics
that we've touched on already in week one.

356
00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:43.080
You can even do sensitivity
analysis to address shaky data.

357
00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:47.090
For example, we might be interested
in knowing at which probability

358
00:23:47.090 --> 00:23:52.300
we become indifferent between contracting
with supplier S, and supplier P.

359
00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:54.750
Whether than saying what
the probability is,

360
00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:57.489
we find out what
the break-even probability is.

361
00:23:58.710 --> 00:24:03.160
Finally, it's easiest to use a fence
that have just a few discreet scenarios.

362
00:24:03.160 --> 00:24:04.120
That's what we did this time.

363
00:24:04.120 --> 00:24:08.060
There are only two scenarios,
a weak market and a strong market.

364
00:24:08.060 --> 00:24:10.440
But again,
the reality can be more complex.

365
00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:14.010
And that's what we're gonna look
at in session two this week.

366
00:24:14.010 --> 00:24:18.040
Finally, it's worth mentioning that
decision trees are widely used in

367
00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:19.170
practice.

368
00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:23.660
IDEA is just a small example that we've
designed to convey the essential ideas.

369
00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:24.390
But in practise,

370
00:24:24.390 --> 00:24:28.920
decision trees are used to evaluate
a really wide range of complex problems.

371
00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:32.630
And I'm gonna list just a few of them that
you can find published in Interfaces, but

372
00:24:32.630 --> 00:24:34.420
they are many many more out there.

373
00:24:34.420 --> 00:24:38.230
One example would be in research and
development licensing.

374
00:24:38.230 --> 00:24:42.790
For example, there's an interfaces article
on Phytopharm, which was deciding whether

375
00:24:42.790 --> 00:24:47.080
to keep developing its products or
to license them.

376
00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:51.290
Eventually Phytopharm was actually
bought out by another Pxharma company.

377
00:24:51.290 --> 00:24:53.440
Another nice example is credit scoring.

378
00:24:53.440 --> 00:24:58.290
There's an Interfaces article on Bank One,
which was subsequently bought by Chase.

379
00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:00.390
And when people apply for credit cards and

380
00:25:00.390 --> 00:25:04.235
other forms of credit, a common thing
to do is to use decision trees.

381
00:25:04.235 --> 00:25:09.585
Is to figure out, whether to accept
that person or to not accept the person.

382
00:25:09.585 --> 00:25:13.515
Finally, there's a nice article
on the eradication of Polio,

383
00:25:13.515 --> 00:25:17.975
in which the Center for Disease Control in
the United States is using decision trees

384
00:25:17.975 --> 00:25:20.455
to figure out what's the best
course of action is.

385
00:25:20.455 --> 00:25:24.095
There also exists different software
packages to help analyse and

386
00:25:24.095 --> 00:25:26.190
manage large decision trees.

387
00:25:26.190 --> 00:25:31.030
They range from single user products,
such as TreePlan, to massive enterprise

388
00:25:31.030 --> 00:25:35.290
wide products such as those made by
DecisionTools and Logical Decisions.

389
00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:40.030
Problems of decision making under
uncertainty are all around us.

390
00:25:40.030 --> 00:25:43.420
We find them whenever we have to
choose among competing actions, and

391
00:25:43.420 --> 00:25:45.980
our choices lead to uncertain outcomes.

392
00:25:45.980 --> 00:25:50.620
In this session, we look to the simple
one stage decision of which supplier to

393
00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:55.255
select, along with a simple model of
uncertainty in the market outcome.

394
00:25:55.255 --> 00:26:00.055
But decisions made under uncertainty can
have more complex decisions, and outcomes,

395
00:26:00.055 --> 00:26:04.525
and in the next two sessions we'll extend
our analysis to cover these cases.

396
00:26:04.525 --> 00:26:07.505
That's it for week four and
session one, see you at session two.